text: Read whole comment, don't be ignorant. Caucasian or Caucasoid doesn't strictly mean white/European, it is in general indo-european and Semitic (middle east). Egyptians back then as they are today are Semitic Caucasoids. the upper class, and nobility in Egypt had lighter skin than the rest of the general population because they wouldn't be out in the fields with the lower classes. Ergo their skin wouldn't darken. lighter skin was a status symbol of wealth because they didn't have to do manual labour. This is not saying they were northern European in looks, they wouldn't look like this, but they definitely WERE NOT sub-Saharan africans, they were not black.  here is an info-graphic from Wikipedia https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cb/Egyptian_races.jpg  Far right is the Egyptian, centre left is a Nubian. Clear cut difference

text: On face value there is really nothing wrong with this as it is a fictional movie, and whom ever finances and produces the movie can cast whomever they  like. But the issue with Ancient Egypt is that the history and knowledge of it was built upon racist Egyptology. Many of these early Egyptologist practice pseudo-science  and scientific racism which built a false narrative of the identity of the Ancient Egyptians. Now there seems to be a resistant among mainstream academics to acknowledge the overwhelming direction of the evidence accumulated in recent times. In academia if you want tenure and the ability to obtain grants for research and work permits from the Egyptian government then you better fall in line and play along. For those reasons, because this fictional film continues to perpetuate a false narrative about Ancient Egypt is why this is so concerning.   "There is now a sufficient body of evidence from modern studies of  skeletal remains to indicate that the ancient Egyptians, especially  southern Egyptians, exhibited physical characteristics that are within  the range of variation for ancient and modern indigenous peoples of the  Sahara and tropical Africa.. In general, the inhabitants of Upper Egypt  and Nubia had the greatest biological affinity to people of the Sahara  and more southerly areas." (Nancy C. Lovell, " Egyptians, physical  anthropology of," in Encyclopedia of the Archaeology of Ancient Egypt,  ed. Kathryn A. Bard and Steven Blake Shubert, ( London and New York:  Routledge, 1999) pp 328-332)    Other ancient Egyptian practices show strong similarities to modern African cultures including divine kingship, the use of headrests, body art, circumcision, and male coming-of-age rituals, all suggesting an African substratum or foundation for Egyptian civilization.."  -- Source: Donald Redford (2001) The Oxford encyclopedia of ancient Egypt, Volume 3. Oxford University Press. p.28    Archaeological evidence also strongly supports an African origin. A widespread northeastern African cultural assemblage, including distinctive multiple barbed harpoons and pottery decorated with dotted wavy line patterns, appears during the early Neolithic (also known as the Aqualithic, a reference to the mild climate of the Sahara at this time). Saharan and Sudanese rock art from this time resembles early Egyptian iconography. Strong connections between Nubian (Sudanese) and Egyptian material culture continue in later Neolithic Badarian culture of Upper Egypt. Similarities include black-topped wares, vessels with characteristic ripple-burnished surfaces, a special tulip-shaped vessel with incised and white-filled decoration, palettes, and harpoons...  Source: Donald Redford (2001) The Oxford encyclopedia of ancient Egypt, Volume 3. Oxford University Press. p.28  "Ancient Egypt belongs to a language group known as 'Afroasiatic'  (formerly called Hamito-Semitic) and its closest relatives are other  north-east African languages from Somalia to Chad. Egypt's cultural  features, both material and ideological and particularly in the earliest  phases, show clear connections with that same broad area. In sum,  ancient Egypt was an African culture, developed by African peoples, who  had wide ranging contacts in north Africa and western Asia." (Morkot, Robert (2005) The Egyptians: An Introduction. Routledge. p. 10)    "Certainly there was some foreign admixture [in Egypt], but basically a  homogeneous African population had lived in the Nile Valley from ancient  to modern times... [the] Badarian people, who developed the earliest  Predynastic Egyptian culture, already exhibited the mix of North African  and Sub-Saharan physical traits that have typified Egyptians ever since  (Hassan 1985; Yurco 1989; Trigger 1978; Keita 1990.. et al.,)... The  peoples of Egypt, the Sudan, and much of East African Ethiopia and  Somalia are now generally regarded as a Nilotic continuity, with widely  ranging physical features (complexions light to dark, various hair and  craniofacial types) but with powerful common cultural traits, including  cattle pastoralist traditions.." (Frank Yurco, "An Egyptological  Review," 1996 -in Mary R. Lefkowitz and Guy MacLean Rogers, Black Athena  Revisited, 1996, The University of North Carolina Press, p. 62-100)

text: Lol, if the only problem this movie had was that it portrayed Egyptians and their gods as white, it could still be a good movie. The problem in this trailer is not the color of the characters' skins - this is a dumb CGI summer blockbuster targeting people looking for a bit of simple-minded fun, expecting faithful adherence to historical and scientific facts from such a movie and getting mad over it is pointless and naive - the problem is that it looks like crap. It looks poorly acted (its star-studded cast is probably working for the paycheck and nothing else), cheesy and corny to cringe-worthy levels, uninteresting and with not-so-great CGI. I have obviously not seen the movie yet, but I will not be paying money to see this one, not because I make a point to boycott historically inaccurate movies out of principle, but because I have a principle of trying to save my money and time for funner, more interesting movies.

text: How to, in my opinion, turn this into something good:  1. Either spend money and hours on good make-up, or use actors and people who at least look like Egyptians.  2. Why all the CGI robot-ish style? We all saw the Transformers movies and some metal god is not new or exciting and looks like a cheap shot. I'd suggest you go for a more Alien look, or at least solely organic. Can be very futuristc and sci-fi esque, but not the cyborg/metal/robot type gods. Also, stay more true to the original Egyptian visions of the gods in terms of color, size, etc.  While you are at it, you can implement the idea of "Alien touch on humans" that could both lead to the idea of religions, early advances in science, etc. Or maybe use different dimensions rather than different worlds.  3. Don't have 'Hollywood' written all over the movie. With this I mean don't make it so foreseeable. If we as viewers can anticipate the entire movie, then what is the idea of making it a Big Screen film? If it is just for a sunday amusement thing then release it on Netflix and be done with it. I am not paying for going to the cinema just to watch a movie I already know the ending of halfway through.  4. Don't rely on action alone. Ancient Egypt was home to some astonishing landscapes and sceneries. Make use of all the visual potential, as well as sound. When that is done, make sure to include a great dose of psychological aspects too. Getting inside the head of the main Antagonists as well as side characters is always a big part of a good movie (imo). Let us experience the movie through the characters, rather than through a big screen while sitting comfortably. Have us on the edge, let us feel like a part of the movie and the story.  5. Last but not least, don't spoil it. Make an epic and interesting trailer, which gives us enough reason to be interested in the movie, as well as wanting to know more. Wanting to 'know more' is what makes people go see it in the cinema. Leave us wanting to know more, experience more. That is what a good trailer is supposed to do.  Looking at this trailer, the movie seems almost done, so I doubt any big changes will happen. I do hope, that someone else will make another attempt at the Egyptian Gods in the future, and that they don't mess it up. It could easily be a big hit on pair with The Hunger Games, James Bond, Batman, etc.

text: It doesn't make much sense to see everybody fighting over our race in a movie trailer. Just to put this to an end, we, Egyptians, are definitely not white, and we are by no means black either. You know the world is not the US. It doesn't have to be white against black in everything. The majority of us have an olive skin tone somewhere in the middle between that of southern Europeans and that of Arabs. A lot of us have Arabic ancestry, but it didn't really change much in terms of our skin color. We can't really tell the difference between those of Arabic background and those who are not based on their looks. And we are pretty sure ancient Egyptians looked very similar to us based on "Fayum mummy portraits" and other things. There is also a minority in the southern part of Egypt called "Nubia" where people have a darker skin tone. "Nubia" was a key player in the history of ancient Egypt, and maybe that's why a lot of people tend to think ancient Egyptians were black. However, they've always been a minority throughout our history.  Can you please stop fighting and just watch the trailer?

text: You've got to be kidding me, another film based around Egypt, that's filled with white actors. Seriously, it is fucked up that they can't get the damn skin color right. If that's not racism & whitewashing, Idk what is. If the film was based around Greek Gods or Norse Gods, this wouldn't be a problem, but Egyptian Gods, these people need to get through their heads that people in Egypt, are not freakin' Caucasian. stop casting white actors. There's no excuse, you're telling me actors like Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson, or Arnold Vosloo(you know, Imhotep from The Mummy) weren't available?  Its 2015, yet the only movies that seem to had the damn skin color right in Egyptian-based films, were The Prince Of Egypt, The Mummy 1 & 2, and its spin-off, The Scorpion King , films from 1998, 1999, 2001, and 2002.  Just think about this real quick, what if there was a film based around the Revolutionary War, and all the Colonists & British were played by black people? People wouldn't like that, would they? Imagine a Greek God film where Zeus, Poseidon, Hades, etc., were played by actors of any other skin color. People would lose their shit over that.  Oh, and if anyone mentions Morgan Freeman in the role of God in Bruce Almighty, its freakin' God, who are we to say what skin color he has? At least with Jesus, its easy to figure out what his skin color really was, considering where his hometown is, Nazareth, Galilee, which is in Israel, so yeah, his skin color isn't freakin Caucasian, like in all the movies, paintings, etc., but that's a discussion for another day. Anyway, back to my point, at least God, can be played by anyone of any skin color, because we don't know what he looks like, so don't bring Morgan Freeman up.

text: First, I'll state I'm no Rick Riordan fan. I just don't get into his books. I did enjoy the original Lightning Thief though. I've read about two of his novels. * I could care less about the race of the actors or the CGI.* Movies don't  always revolve around race. But I do understand the complaint in regards to the setting and the characters. In the film industry, it's about the director making intelligent choices, actors' ability to act and the power of storytelling that comes together. The Egyptians were not all painted as "brown or dark" people. The actual Pharaohs sometimes were of lighter skin and believed to be superior above the population. So you mentioning racism now has already become outdated. Plus, these gods mentioned are the Ennead. They can look however they want. They don't care what mortals think about how they look. They express their appearance in anyway they see fit. Heck, Osiris has green skin and Atum is sometimes presented having blue skin.   My only issue with this film is how the plot seems to be executed from the trailer. It doesn't seem very strong. Osiris isn't even mentioned, at all. That's so....UGH. Go look up the Legend of Osiris. Horus never went after Set because "he stole his eye" and then Set stole the throne immediately in a simple asskicking contest. That never happened in the story.  Also "The Eye", is not a physical object. Wadjet was relevant to that at one point during the mythos. She's one of the older godesses that gets skipped pretty often in regards to this pantheon. The Eye is more of an abstract entity that can act upon the will of its master at the time or personified instead as a servant of the Patron Pharaoh. :/  Not gonna lie though, their "Sheuts" look kinda interesting with the metallic exoskeleton. Still the fact they refer to Set in the description as a god of darkness. *CRINGE* He's not. And Horus tricked Set into giving up the throne by illegitimate means since he couldn't compete against him on equal terms. So in this story. Cheater's Win and gain the favor Maat. *sigh* I wish this wasn't called Gods of Egypt. It comes as off pretentious of what the Ennead were and "only another movie based on abridged mythos."  I want to dislike this film but at the same time, I want to like it because  I'm very fond of the Ogdoad, the Ennead and the other major gods such as Re and Apep. The stories told and philosophy of the ancients of  are quite interesting. And we haven't really had a film with a visually appealing or vibrant landscape in regards to the area surrounding the Nile.   It's so inaccurate from a story perspective, but I hope at least it'll be entertaining It'll probably be another guilty pleasure to see it only for that.  But one can be an optimist. :)

text: It's most unfortunate that today some whites have a major problem with ancient Egyptians being displayed as black.  Anthropologists have already proven their origins were of Sub-saharan origin, not Semitic and not Greek.  All of those of African descent came from East Africa anyway.  The body of Cleopatra's sister has recently been found in Turkey and it was concluded that her mother was of African ancestry sub-saharan, not semitic or Greek, therefore Cleopatra's mother was black.  Now the father of Cleopatra was from Macedonia and ruled an empire and Egypt like the other Greek islands fell under his reign.  So in other words her mother was indigenous to Egypt while the father was not.  Hence the ancient Egyptians were of African sub-saharan origin although over time they did begin like other nations to enter marry with other nationalities.  Some of the Greek philosophers have already described this in their writings.  Why do some, not all!! Whites have a real problem with a black African people being anything other than subserviant.  In the tomb of Ramses III an image of the four nationalities were found with color and titles given for each race of people.  The Nubians and the ancient Egyptians were both painted as black while the semitic, Asians, and Europeans as either white or very light peach in color.  The only difference between the depiction of the Egyptians and the Nubians was their clothing.  In my opinion we should remember that every nation of people have had a time of triumph hence there is no need to continue degrading and dismissing the history of others out of spite and arrogance.

text: One must remember humans don't fit neatly into 17th Century connotations of race. Humans are clinal, which means gradual change in an inherited characteristic across the geographic range of a species. Africans can be light skin, dark skin or medium and so can people from the Middle east or Asia. For instance their are dark skin people in Pakistan, India and Melanesia. With that said the modern Egyptians may have some ancestral blood line to the ancients but they are highly admixed with centuries of foreign immigration into Egypt. The darker Egyptians in the South, Sudanese and Ethiopians are probably a closer representative to the Ancient Egyptians. Historically, there has been an attempt by scholars and Egyptologist to remove Egypt from Africa, only in recent scholarship has there been a willingness to develop more research in their cultural affinities. But Ancient Egypt was culturally and spiritually African, they practiced the same burials, rituals, Kingship, animal deity worship as their surrounding neighbors. People can debate about race as race is an arbitrary 17th Century classification system but Culturally the Ancient Egyptians were African .

I hope people realise that the ancient egyptians were not african ! If you study and read the ancient papyrus and hieroglyphs,  the egyptians themselves talk about how they fought against the dark skinned people for control of lower egypt for years along with fighting with them, they were also fighting with other tribes who wanted power in the region as well. there was one time that one pharaoh even asked for help by the nubians, because crime was so rampant by war lords in the region. after that fight they left with jewels,golds horses! the nubian king piye love egypt so much he even was buried in a mud style pyramid  but this was all way after the pyramids and a lot of the great temples were already built! egyptians and nubians always had a difficult relationship, they are even depicted on hieroglyphs with severed heads! or the brown skinned egyptian people and pharaohs stomping on them ! the pharaohs  even drew up a truce several times with the nubians, the kind of nubia sold his own people as guards and slaves/workers to the egyptians. the king of nubia also exchanged herbs/exotic animals of africa,ivory, gold as well. You can tour how different their culture was even today! there pyramids hardly stood the test of time! all these monuments were made of mud brick! not granite and stone! when they drew the nubians on hieroglyphs, when they captured them as slaves or as portraits they were always black, if all egyptians are black then why do they depict themselves as a light brown. why wouldn't they all be black in colour ? not only that they despised foreigners as well! its apparent once you take time to read the papyrus and hieroglyphs.  some of it is rather disgusting really, comparing them to dirt, how they collected their severed hands! also it's not like this movie excluded african americans they to are in the movie along whites united just as life ought to be ! race hate/racism isnt just against one particular race it's against all races and any race can be racist!  its disgusting and we all should be squashing this crap and uniting !

text: This reminds me of the discussion around Exodus: Gods and Kings. Ridley Scott on the subject of whitewashing stated the choice of cast was not racially motivated, but rather a consequence of a Hollywood reality, they need the big names to draw to crowds. Egyptian or North African actors are simply not well known enough (in Hollywood).  Why are the most well known actors (in Hollywood) white? The answer seems to be, In a majority white country there will be more white actors, it follows they will be a majority of the actors that are able to draw crowds. However, there seems to be something off when the black minority that makes up 14% of the population, not a small number, do not get to have the lead role in a big production, unless they are:  1. Denzel Washington  2. Will Smith  No one else! The fact that these two actors are actually able to break free of this suggests Hollywood, in the end, cares more about earnings than whitewashing. It's just that whitewashing has proven a very successful business model, as it aims for the biggest market. It's playing it safe.  The response is often "the people that make these movies have a duty to change that paradigm!"  The reality of big budget moviemaking is that currently very few investors will make a multi million dollar investment to promote social justice ideals. They just want the best, or maybe the safest return on their investment. For this very reason the indie movie scene is full of diversity. Lower budgets equal more artistic freedom. As soon as you start spending someone else's millions the dynamics change.  So the answer is really, really simple if you don't like this. Don't go see it. Instead, go support a filmmaker that DOES support your ideals. Because realistically, the only way a big budget movie will exist that prioritizes (selective) historical accuracy over star power is when it will make them more money.

Yes, some whites like the Hittites and Greeks interacted with the Egyptians but those were few and far between. Everyone in this movie should be between Middle Eastern or East African. Egypt is precisely located at the geocentric of the earth. Most of the people who existed in that civilization were a mixture of African, European, and Middle Eastern descent. text: This movie just looks bad.  As for the numerous comments on the CGI, I think all movies that rely heavily on CGI tend to look kind of bad/cheap.  People commenting on "good" CGI examples like Avatar and Inception.  Avatar was just as bad as this IMO.  CLEARLY CGI and the aliens looked like a video game IMO.  The entire planet was CGI and obviously so.  Did the blatant use of CGI make the movie bad though?  No.  Avatar was alright (not AMAZING, like most people say.... I guess I'm not amazed by the overused plot line nor am I a tree hugger).  As for Inception.  That's a Nolan film and he notoriously tries to use as little CGI as possible in all his movies.  Most of the "cgi" you think you saw in Inception was likely not CGI.  In fact I really can't think of a scene in that movie that used CGI other than the bending streets/horizons and that city like deal on/near the beach in his dream.  Nowhere near the amount of CGI in Inception as there is in this movie and Avatar.... films made solely dedicated to CGI.... it's pretty much becoming a genre itself..... CGI genre.  Sin City and the 300 movies are other examples of this genre I'm labeling as the CGI Genre.  where everything but the actors (for the most part) is entirely CGI.

text: An Open Letter To Lionsgate Entertainment,  Dear Sirs, I understand the difficulty in making a film on this scale with unknown actors, but I and others must object strongly to the cast you have assembled to partake in this film. I have studied Egyptian mythology all my life, and the ancient Egyptians clearly did NOT portray their gods as human beings, and yet the cast is entirely human. The gods of Egypt were clearly depicted with green, blue, or gold skin, and most had animal heads. Well, it's high time such an under-represented group was given the treatment it deserves in Hollywood. My own father is a purple elephant man, and every time one of these dang films is made, I have to explain to him that his own group is going to be callously represented by the average white or black man yet again. How dare they cast a black man as Thoth, the god of wisdom, when Thoth was very plainly represented as having multiple skin tones (depending on the artist) and a green ibis head! Where are the skin-color-changing ibis people in this movie? If this racist insensitivity continues, I'm afraid I and my family will never give you a cent again. Yours Faithfully, Rear Admiral Seymour Botty (Mrs.)

text: Screw up the mythology and no one bats an eye.  Screw up the casting and everyone goes insane.  Seriously though, what's with the demonization of the non-Osiris/Horus gods? If it's not Anubis, then it's Set. In Egyptian mythology, Apep/Apophis is the actual evil, trying to eat Ra every night. Set is actually more of an anti-hero, since he's the one that protects Ra by continuously killing Apophis each night, not to mention being the god of storms and the desert. And it seems that they're setting up (pun intended) Apophis to be an analogue to the Kraken from Clash of the Titans, as seen at 1:48, to be summoned by Set. They could've had the film be accurate to mythology and be entertaining, but they didn't really care.

text: ''Were the Ancient Egyptians Africans? What colour was their skin? Yes. Egypt is in Africa and there are many cultural links to other African civilisations. If we look at the skin colour and also facial features on representations of Egyptians, many are what we would consider today to be Black African. Skin colours on temple and wall reliefs show ranges between dark brown and black, which is typical of what we see today with regard to people of Black African descent or origin. Furthermore, Nubians, a group who are accepted universally as Black Africans are, like their neighbours from Kemet, shown on reliefs with both jet black and red-brown skin and can be distinguished as Nubians by their short wigs. Many statues have lost their original skin colour. Sometimes colours were used by the Egyptians symbolically, so for example a statue of a god or royal person would painted gold to represent immortality. If we leave colour aside for a moment, we can also find out a great deal from looking at the facial features shown on Egyptian statues. Here, there can be no doubt that we are dealing with people who were African. Faces were broad with high cheekbones and the jaws are typically strong. The noses are also broad and the lips are generally full and fleshy in appearance.'' http://www.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/dept/ant/egypt/kemet/virtualkemet/faq/  In conclusion - sorry folks but Egyptians were a mix of African (black) Greeks, Persians etc..Use your brains, understand how people were moving from one area to another...Humans did not evolve in isolation, if they did we would have sub-species. There are no sub-species of humans...even racists are not considered a sub species (more the pity). Educate yourselves ..there is no excuse nowadays for total ignorance.

text: Why are the gods of Egypt white? Could a movie about East/South Asian gods cast Caucasian actors as the gods? How would people react if Nicole Kidman was Shiva and Brad Pitt was Vishnu? Could the gods of Native Americans be Caucasian?   This is extremely racist no matter how you look at it. (Unless it's Cleopatra's era, all these white people are anachronistic). This movie is an offensive, gross appropriation of African history. "Africans didn't make the pyramids, it was the Gerald Butlers and the Jaime Lannisters" is what this movie is implying. What is worse than white pharaohs are the white gods. The gall to cast white actors as the gods of an African civilization! Why did no one put a stop to this blasphemy? All the fuss people threw about Idris Elba playing a Norse god and Hollywood has the audacity to make all white people the gods of an African Kingdom? (I reiterate that this is pre-Cleopatra, pre-Ptolemy and when these "white" Greeks arrived in Egypt, the religion had been established for millenia.)   These gods were the gods worshipped by Nefertiti and the other pharaohs and none of these pharaohs were white (as evidenced by their statues and busts), so why would they worship or create gods who were white?

text: Sigh... let me break down why I (and I believe many others) are disappointed by this film.  Its not just this film by itself that is so problematic its that this film is the latest in a long line of Hollywood films where Egyptians are portrayed as white people.  This Hollywood proclivity is only a reflection of the old belief among white academics and white cultures that Egyptians were this random group of white people in Africa.  You see many people of European descent have been fascinated with Egypt for a long time.  However, admitting that Africans had an advanced ancient civilization that had a big impact on the ancient European founders of "western" civilization is difficult when you also believe that Africans are sub-humans only fit for manual labor.  So why not pretend the ancient Egyptians were white and try to convince everyone of that as well?!  On top of that there are so few Hollywood roles that fit people of color well ESPECIALLY when it comes to period films, and this one comes around, which would be PERFECT but its..all..white.  As a person of African descent I would love to see a representation of my ancient ancestors on film just like anyone else, but since there is no hint of ancient West African history or folklore, I feel like Egypt is a good compromise.  Yes I know the average ancient Egyptian probably looked just as different from the average African American as from the average European descent person, but damn it they could have at least got some brown actors.  If not North African or middle eastern They could been different and cast some Latino or Desi actors.  Anyway, as much shit as I talked about this movie the special effects look too good to pass up and the story seems pretty fun so I'll probably catch it on Netflix or Redbox or something, but I am Definitely not spending money to watch more white washing of ancient Egypt. #Disappointed... #Again

text: This movie actually looks entertaining. But everyone has to know that ancient Egyptians did not look like that. Black and White wasn't a concept back then but if you look at ancient paintings and statues they were definitely closer to what we call "black" today. They used red-brown and jet black to paint their skin. Look to Ethiopians and Eritreans to see what Kemetians looked like.  The reason black people get so upset when they make movies like this is because we are written out of history. It sucks when the only images you see of people like you are only slaves and criminals. Even if we are not directly descended from them It is empowering to see people who look like you do great things.  Final point; its not up to Hollywood to represent us correctly. We should make our own movies if we want to see people like us winning.

text: Damn shame! In 2015 their still casting white people to play ancient egyptians. Many people may argue and say well its just a fantasy movie about gods and goddesses with super powers, but you have to look at the bigger picture of where people are coming from so you can understand why we get upset about shit like this. First of all for many years movies and historial documentaries have been casting whites to play ancient egyptians and brainwashing many people into thinking that the ancient egyptians were something other than black people. Some may argue and say that the ancient egyptians were mixed with other races and ethnic groups which is true but that was much later in ancient Egypt's history during the last dynasties during the Roman Empire and when the arab muslims invaded Egypt around 600 A.D.. That is why many modern egyptians resemble mediterranean and arabian people but you can't compare the later generations of egyptians to the older generations that were pure black egyptians prior to the times before they where invaded because that would be like comparing the modern population of americans of mostly blacks and whites to the original population of native americans who where in the Americas before the europeans and africans came to their land.  Another thing people need to realize, just because you see ancient egyptian images of people with narrow noses, thin lips, and straight hair does not mean that the ancient egyptians were not black people. Black africans came in many shades of brown and phenotypes way before the foreigners invaded Africa because black people are the first people on the planet and are the ones who evolved and produced all the other races on the planet. Anthropologist that studied ancient egyptian bones have concluded that most ancient egyptians remsemble black east africans like the somali, oromo, masai, nubian, afar, rendille, and beja ethnic groups. Even today many modern egyptians are less mixed and more pure black like thier ancestors and mainly reside in southern Egypt like the city of Luxor and they are many shades of brown. text: Ancient Egyptians weren't Black, but they weren't White either. Heck, they didn't look like modern Egyptians either. They are an ancient, distinct people who we know very little about biologically. Unlike some other ancient civilizations, we can't assume that they look similar to their modern day counterpart. Egypt is/was so close to so many other civilizations that you can't try to group it with any other. Also, just because Egypt is located on Africa does not mean that they are the same as all other Africans. That's like saying French=German or Canadian=Mexican. Other people argue stuff like "What if there was a movie about Slavery in the US and the slaves are all white?" What kind of a question is that? Slavery was obviously a racial issue, so race is obviously an important factor in the casting. This movie does not deal with any racial issues. It's a movie about a civilization of people whose looks are more or less unknown to us being made in a country which is predominantly white. Stop trying to turn everything into an issue about race.

Most were passable but they did bring in cash (pretty much like what SyFy does with Sharknado type movies). A few became classics because directors were doing a LOT with very little budget. Nowadays studious are going overboard with colossal budgets for movies that, pretty much, have no replay value outside Netflix. Throwing money at it won't make it a classic, or a hit, when there's no substance behind it.

text: Ancient Egypt was actually pretty large in scope, and lasted for a very long time indeed, having several ethnic groups over time. However, early egypt did NOT have the nubian ethnic group as a part of it.  The kingdom of kush is where the aforementioned nubian ethnic group is from, it was partially conquered by egypt several times, hence why nubians are a part of egypt, and why a lot of egyptian art features battles between white-brown people(egyptians) and brown-black people(nubians). There was from what I can understand, a single nubian dynasty, the Twenty-fifth Dynasty(Memphis, under foreign control of Napata, Nubia).  In short. black actors are just as inacccurate as west europeans and their descendants, sub-saharan africa had very little to do with (early)egypt, and as there is a dearth of egyptian actors, there is no appropriate cast of actors within hollywood.  For people complaining about "cultural appropriation" you certainly do it a lot. But, hey, if some of you took the time to research your claims, you wouldn't be ideological nutbags, and that would be just terrible, wouldn't it?  TL;DR : Egyptians are/were not sub-saharan africans, be amazed at this self-evident fact.

text: Interesting comments; Egyptians were light and dark complected with many in between. The sun is not inhibited throughout must of Africa: it's Greek for "the land of the Sun", unless I'm wrong. Many long term inhabitants of Greece are quite dark (olive possessing the ability to tan darkly) and do not easily burn in the sun; the Greeks differentiated between North Africa and Greece, noting less cloud cover.   It would be easy to suppose that the lightest Ancient Egyptians had the ability to tan (were olive), most would probably be naturally tan (and quite dark when they were outside for long periods of time) and the darkest were similar to darker Nubians south of Upper Egypt (southern Egypt was the origin). Really, I believe the Egyptians were quite a mix of people (much like everywhere else, but we forget).  Having Brazilian people, or Latin people would not be wrong; having darker African people play them would not be wrong; having Europeans that tan darkly play some of them would not be wrong; lightening the entire population too drastically would ignore the natural climate and suggest that an invading army had success or a drastic migration recently occurred..   So, the movie is not super horrible (it could be worse).

text: To all those defending the casting choices for this movie: I know your point is that, it's mythology so it doesn't have to be accurate. Also, if it wanted to be accurate, no one knew the ethnicity of the Egyptians way back then. Third, why complain here when, in the Thor movies, Heimdall was portrayed by a Black man, you guys didn't complain then. Here's my response:  People did throw a hissy fit when Heimdall was portrays by Idris Elba. Now, imagine how much more pissed they'd be if it was reversed. ALL THE NORSE gods were Black, and only Heimdall was White. Weird right? Okay, that's what's going on here so ... yeah. Stop making excuses for Hollywood. One token casting here and there doesn't forgive each time a "MAIN CHARACTER" is played by someone of an ethnicity that off. Particularly caucasian because, they have tons of starring roles already and a long history of already bumping off minorities to play the role of minorities. So yeah. it's also about sharing. Once again, they assume recognizable white actors would draw in more audiences and that's all there is too it. They don't care how offensive and odd the casting is. Myself, I'm pretty forgiving. If they're portraying a character that is suppose to be a specific ethnicity, if they're in the ball park, I'm fine. It would be nice if they were exact, but that can't always happen. But to be this far off is insulting.

text: As an Egyptologist, I'm struggling to deal with the fact this set looks completely artificial. At least with The Mummy movies there was earthy naturalness with the sand and limestone. The monuments looked rough and aged as they would in real life. And from what I understand, the first 2 Mummy movies were filmed in Egypt. But graphics have improved so much that now the sets looks totally unrealistic, and, no doubt, they don't film on location but with sets and green screens, which is probably much of the problem. With the kind of money film companies have these days you'd expect an element of authenticity to their films. Lets hope they've at least consulted experts with this myth. From what the trailer shows, the myth seems to reflect the writings in hieroglyphical texts, but no doubt they have added elements that do sway from the original writings.

text: All North Africans as well as Somalis originally inhabited the Horn, however Ancient North Africans including the Ancient Egyptians decided to split and travel northwards eventually dispersing and inhabiting the area of the Northern Continent ranging from Morocco to Ancient Egypt. Obviously then Natural Selection and their increased distance from the Equator allowed them to become different indigenous phenotypes. The Ancient Egyptians even remembered their original homeland and the Exact spot (Puntland). They even journeyed on what they considered Sacred and Holy pilgrimages to The Puntland region of Somalia which they called the land of their forefathers, the land of Perfume and more famously The Land Of The Gods and they left behind evidence that you can find to this day. This has been proven genetically, geographically and archaeologically, but just because Somalia is a lesser known country with a lesser population it's refused to be credited it with it's Undervalued and Rich History. I must also admit that this is partially SOME Somalis fault as they refuse history that pre-dates Islam which they consider "Non-Islamic" which is pretty Sad. Now my post is obviously contradictory to the infamous "Somalis = Black +Arab" myth which is a poor and desperate attempt to explain the features of Somalis and why Somalis range from lightish tan to brown skin with their particular Hair textures. This however doesn't include other East Africans like the inhabitants of Uganda which is relatively close to Somalia and Kenya which borders Somalia since they don't share the Same features/blood.

text: It's a little disheartening to see how uneducated, as well a narrow minded some people are in the comments. Yes all ancient Egyptians weren't white, however that does not mean due to the geographical location they were all black. They were also middle eastern and Macedonian. Cleopatra herself was part Greek. Due to trade and mixing of cultures, there were many crossings in the gene pool that lead to black, tan, and/or olive skin tones. Lets not narrow in on one race to support an argument. However, it is without a doubt ridiculous that they cast white British men to portray Gods of Egypt. Even with the smaller numbers of POC actors/actresses, they could have worked harder to make this historically accurate and not as culturally insensitive.

text: To both sides of the race debate...  The classical view concerning Egypt and race (which let's remember is a social construct) is that Semitic speaking people's came down from around the areas of northern Arabia and brought their language to a North African (i.e. Black & Berber) population.  We have their physical remains, we've had them since the late 1800s - dry sand is very forgiving to artifacts and dead bodies.  These corpse-burying semites formed a ruling elite for a while, and were eventually absorbed by a wider black population (on account of recessive genes), leaving Egypt as a giant melting pot when it comes to skin colour, religion, and language...    Let's not forget, Egypt = the Nile, which is massive and stretches very far south into the heart of Nubia, and all the way to the mediterranean basin in the north, which was largely sailed by traders of Old Europe, the Levant and North Africa.  There were [at least] 3000 years of Egyptian history before Cleopatra, and LOTS can happen in that time: Hyksos (semitic) invasions, Nubian/Kushite invasions, Assyrian & Persian invasions, Greek invasions, and so forth.  Egypt had, and currently has no 'race', get over yourselves.  Ancient Egypt is not an unchangeable cultural monolith; it is not a platonic archetype in the sky; it was not white, it was not black, it was not 'multicultural' - these are all modern notions which had no meaning back then, and should not be retro-projected onto the past for our own self-legitimacy.

text: The case most comments are arguing about here is whether ancient Egyptians were black or not. Well, let me tell you something, IT IS A GOD DAMN MOVIE. It is all about fiction and entertainment and there is no real history in describing the Ancient Egyptian MYTHOLOGY. Because the gods of Egypt were depicted in many skin tones, white, bronze, red toned, black, very black as in the black of a matte car finish and even blue and green. About Egyptians, it frustrates me to assume that Egyptians were black as in Ethiopian black or African American black, because first of all, I am Egyptian and I know how my people look like. Yes, I can hear you over there, the one who is saying modern Egyptians are not like Ancient Egyptians, due to the successive invasions and racial mixing and blah blah blah... But here is what you don't know, there are several villages in Egypt, in upper Egypt to be exact, the place of ancient Egyptians, that are very much like closed societies, they marry from each other, they don't mix with other outsiders. Maybe those resemble Ancient Egyptians to some extent and they have kinda mocha colored skin, like Latinos. And if you gonna depend it on the facial features of the statues and ancient Egyptian drawings, I gotta tell you that I see Egyptians everyday that have very curly thick hair, big nostrils and thick lips, but have light skin. Modern Egyptians have a complexion that is very dark in outdoor summer days and white in winter nights. I have a bronze mocha face and hands, while full body is like light Latte with a pinkish tone. And from a geographical point of view, Ancient Egyptians should not be compared to Deep Savanna's Africans, because Egypt is not on the equator and just because it is a desert doesn't mean it should have black people. The temperature in Egypt normally range between 30 degrees celsius in summer days and 8 degrees celsius in winter nights ( sometimes in rare occasions reaching 45 in summer and 1.5 in winter ), It is not like the Equator in Africa where the lowest temperature is 20 degrees. The climate in Egypt is very fluctuating from season to season, so from an evolutionary perspective, Ancient Egyptians should have more light skin, because there is not much heat all year round to affect their coloration, they should have some body hair to protect them in winter (unlike Black Africans who have scarce body or facial hair). And no offence meant here, but Ancient Egyptians were pretty advanced compared to any body in their time, and way more advanced than any African culture been until the 20th century. They didn't acquire their knowledge and development overnight. They went through thousands of years of development, before they could build the first pyramid which was build 7000 years ago. So even if they originated from central Africa, they would have evolved from that point and they wouldn't look like Black Africans nor in facial or body features nor in skin color or tone.

Now, most would say that the so called "black race" comes from Noah's son Ham, and that he was cursed to be the servants of his brothers. The bible actually says that Ham's son, Canaan will be cursed. But with that being said, we can actually trace the lineage of the so called black to Ham's sons, Kush (ethiopia) which also means burnt skin, Phut or (Put) which is today's Libya, Salum, which is today's Jerusalum, and Mizriam, which is Egypt. Now, If it is true that Ham is the father of what man calls the black race, then why wouldn't Ham's sons not be black like their father?   Also, If science is true and accurate, hows does a non-black man produce the genes of a black man when science says that brown eyes and dark skin is dominant versus lighter skin and eyes being the recessive traits? If we choose to read the bible and with accept the book as being authentic, we would find that until the time of Noah and the building of the ark was the first and only time that the world experienced rain. If there is no rain, then there isn't snow, and if there isn't snow then there isn't ice. the climate was likely tropical and sunny. People would have need the melanin in their skin for protection. the skin that we call white was more suitable for a cooler climate which allowed the skin to absorb the sun rays for vitamin D.   In college, one of my math professors was from Egypt; she looked very similar to my aunt. A Black Egyptian by the name of Mostafa Hefney said that Egypt is a black and brown nation. He stated that he classified himself as an Arab Muslim. He also stated that the Arabs are a black ethnic group. When ask about whites in Egypt, Hefney stated that whites came to Egypt during the Roman and Greek empires and mixed with a small population of the people. If we follow history, the Greek and the Roman empire did not arrive until the new testament according to the bible. This would mean that a black ethic group built the pyramids and structures in Ethiopia, the Sudan as well as Egypt a thousand years before whites came along. And according to history, the Arabs were the last to invade and remain today along with the original inhabitants. We must not forget Hams grandson Nimrod. According to the bible, Nimrod found favor in the eyes of God and established his empire by building the tower of babel in Modern day Babylon Iraq. Hefney, who is a PHD here in America has a pending court decision on rather the U.S. courts will re-classify Hefney as being a Black Egyptian.  If you choose not to believe what I am saying, just post factual information the can refute what I have stated, and If you want references start with the black Egyptian by the name of Mostafa Hefney. You can also read the work and findings from Professor Ivan Van Sertima. and lastly, read the work of Yosef Ben Johannon, he is an Ethiopian Jew. Lastly, we should all be appalled at the so called education that Western civilization offers. Our educational system seems to be structured to acknowledge only European and American accomplishments. text: I wanted to remain quiet, but seeing the level of idiocy festering in this comment chain became overbearing, and I mean from both sides. Firstly none of you have a basic understanding of biology, arguing "BLACK, WHITE, YABADABA DOOO." Race is a social construct that became prevalent at the turn of the 15th century, orchestrated by the Spanish right around the time Columbus allegedly "rediscovered" America. The Spanish used race as a way to classify superiority, the lighter the skin the more intelligent and civilized, the darker vice versa- then when western Europe arose from the depth of chaos and began world domination they too indoctrinated racial classifications. With the recent discovery of haplogroups biologist have finally dispelled race as anything biological, that fallacy has been burned to the ground, RACE DOES NOT EXIST IN A BIOLOGICAL SENSE. There is more DNA diversity in west African villages alone, than between Africa and Europe. What race does identify is our evolution in respected geographical locations, that is all, we all belong to one species and one race: homosapiens and human.           Now moving to the matter of what "color" the actual Egyptians were, not the offspring of invaders we have now. Egyptians were dark skinned Africans, as all of Africans were dark skin. Not as dark as sub saharan africans but the lightest most likely being my complexion, as unbiased greek philosophers describe. Why? That's easy, were they evolved. Africa having a more mild to hot climate, and being closer to the equator caused the adaptation of dark skin, that's just how the people acclimated to that niche. Europe being more north and colder, also due to their enclosure in caves, is what led to their pale skin. The difference is also shown in Southeast Asians vs Northwest Asians. Arabs are mulattos, just like now Egyptians, North Africa and Northeast Africa suffered millennia of invasions from Europe, which led to the mixture of features and lighter skin. Returning to the Sumerian epoch, they too were dark as the "middle eastern" climate is very similar to North African climate, which should disseminate any confusion as to why ancient Middle Easterners would be light and not Egyptians.      Lastly stop trying to separate Africa into categories, it's funny how they always divide Africa in terms of civilization, but not Europe. Southern Europe and North Europe didn't have the same accomplishments, why don't we classify Greece and Rome as Southern European achievements instead of "European" it's nothing but another diminutive tactic Europeans use called "divide and conquer." Egypt is in Africa, an African achievement, and represents all of Africa (as well as Greece being a European achievement), just as subsaharan Africa had many great civilizations, one being the Axum Empire which was a world superpower in it's prime, but not many of you would know that. Arabs stop trying to claim Egypt, it was not a Arab civilization, you guys came in at 700AD, no earlier. You guys don't want to be considered African until Egypt is brought up, then all of a sudden you're jumping the band wagon. Want to be a part of Africa then admit that the middle east is still Africa, I don't know why it changed from North East Africa into the Middle East, probably just another way to separate Africans.      Also I saw a lot of that "Ramses had a picture of him killing hundreds of Nubians." If you people had any eruditeness in Egypt's antiquity you'd know that yes, Egyptians and Nubians engaged in many conflicts, as have all civilizations, conflict has been a part of the world since recorded history, you'd also know that King Nermer united Egypt and Nubia initiating Egypt's "golden age" which is what most people know Egypt by, because it's also the time that the pyramids were constructed sometime around 3500BCE and 2500 BCE. Also Egyptians believe that the originated from Somalia, which the called the land of Punt, or something of the sort, meaning the holy land. And what do Somalians look like??? Thank you. I swear racism breed the biggest idiots, how can you be so hateful you, obfuscate, fabricate, and just plain lie in order to eradicate African achievements? Yes Africa has had many great civilizations, were a great people, AND STILL ARE. I'm african and proud, if I was born European I'd be proud, be proud of your ancestry and stop stealing others. That's the only way to truly deconstruct racism.  EDIT: Will not be replying to comments.

text: Hollywood definitely white washes the heck out of history. Black and White are social constructs used for segregation, discrimination, and trying to make one color seem superior or inferior to another.   Egyptians are definitely people of color, and even the "whitest" Egyptian (especially back then probably wouldn't have looked like anyone from this cast). BUT, it wouldn't be historically accurate to use an all Ghanaian or Nigerian cast either. One man named Ham (son of Noah) is the father of Egyptians, Libyans, Ethiopians, Nubians, and more. That's many shades of people on one huge continent just from one man, and he was only one of Noah's sons (smh I just opened the gate for Bible hating trolls). I'm saying all this to say that there is more than just "black and white". Scientifically, we are all one race (human).   The problem isn't the casting as much as it is White Supremacy, which goes beyond just Hollywood. I'm not talking about KKK White Supremacy; I'm talking about the idea that White/European is more acceptable, beautiful, intelligent looking, safer looking, heroic, easier to stomach, etc...... than any other "race" or nationality. White Supremacy can be very subtle. It is why there are more pictures of a European looking Jesus than there are pictures of a Hebrew, Palestinian, or Middle Eastern looking Jesus. It's a problem, but it can never be  fixed until people admit that it is.

text: Guys can we please talk about something other than the casting on here?Â  I completely respect how people feel and I understand the whole whitewashingÂ annoyance going on here, but unlike most of you I'm not totally focused on that aspect of the film.Â  This is a fantasy adventure movie, it's not meant to be taken seriously folks.Â  It's not based on a true story or based on true events, it's just a movie based on a culture's legends.Â  I understand people are on here to voice their opinions, which I respect wholeheartedly, but I find it disheartening when all I see are comments talking about theÂ whitewashing over and over again which span into different long discussions.Â  Is no one here to discuss the special effects (yes it's all CGI I know but it still looks cool), or the story,Â or at least say whether they think it looks good or not, or even compare it to other movies coming out this year?Â  I really wish that the topic of conversation could just switch gears already to something other than the race of the actors, because I'm not sure too many reviewers will make their reviews based solely on their races.Â  I know I won't if I see it.Â  And just like the comment below me stated, "having an Egyptian playing an Egyptian is near impossible for Hollywood."Â  I mean who knows, this could turn out to be really good if people just give it a chance, actor races put aside.

text: Yes, the Ancient Egyptians were not white. History shows us that. This isn't a shocker.  3100 BC - Narmer is first pharaoh. (Google him. His nose looks pretty African if you ask me). He unified Upper & Lower Egypt (Lower Egypt was in NORTH AFRICA. Upper Egypt was THE BOTTOM OF THE NILE BY NUBIA)  2650 BC - First stone pyramid built   2550 BC - Pyramids of Giza built   2150 BC -  For about 150 years, Upper and Lower Egypt had different rulers.  2055 BC - Mentuhotep II gained control of entire country  1650 BC - Hyksos rulers took control of Delta region, brought new tech like the chariot   1550 BC - Hymose threw Hyksos out of Egypt, unifying Lower & Upper Egypt as pharaoh  1473 BC - Hatsheptut became pharaoh. She ruled for 15 years.  1353 BC - Akhenaten becomes pharaoh. He changes Egyptian religion.  1336 BC - Tutankhamun is pharaoh for nine years.  1279 BC - Ramesses II became pharaoh   1050 BC - Upper and Lower Egypt split   728 BC - Nubian emperor Piy conquered Egypt   671 BC - Assyrians invade Egypt, and conquer it in 669 BC  525 BC - Persians conquer Egypt   332 BC - Alexander the Great conquers Egypt.  305 BC - Ptolemy becomes the pharaoh   196 BC - Rosetta Stone carved   51 BC - Cleopatra is pharaoh   31 BC - Battle of Actium  30 BC - Cleopatra dies   350 AD - Last use of hieroglyphic writing   642 AD - Egypt conquered by Arabs   820 AD - Caliph al Mamun entered the Great Pyramid  969 AD - City of Cairo founded  1517 AD -  Ottoman Turks ruled Egypt  The Ancient Egyptians OBVIOUSLY were not white.  Upper Egypt was at the bottom of the Nile River, by Nubia. Lower Egypt was at the very top.   History literally shows us this, and people still try to say otherwise. I don't see how you can fight against facts  There is a reason why Egyptians look so much different. Thousands of years of mixing and interbreeding has now changed their appearance.  The fun thing is, a fact is still a fact, whether or not you believe in it.

text: There's so much misinformation in this comment section. I am Egyptian. It's offensive to me when people say my ancestors were "black" because they very most likely looked like modern-day Egyptians, who are neither "black" nor "white". Ancient Egyptians did not portray themselves as black, in ancient Egyptian art, they differentiated themselves from Nubians by painting Nubians darker than Egyptians (As a side note, Nubians are an ethnic group that mostly resides within the borders of modern-day Egypt, so today, they are as much Egyptians as anyone else, even though they still maintain a separate culture, language and ethnicity. However, in ancient times, they were a separate nation from the Ancient Egyptians, so this demonstrates how both ethnic groups have been mostly maintained from ancient times).   We are Semitic people but not Arabs. Arabic is the main language in Egypt today, but historically, Arabs are an ethnic group separate from ancient Egyptians.   This categorization based on skin colour doesn't even make much sense, Ethiopians are also semitic people, but are still considered "black" today, even though they look very different from West Africans, and probably share more biological similarities with Egyptians than with West Africans. The only reason to be having the debate about what colour the skin of Ancient Egyptians was, is to determine who best to represent the true ancient Egyptians in film, and it definitely makes a lot more sense to use modern Egyptians, who are no doubt the closest biological descendants of ancient Egyptians. Even using other semitic people (other North Africans, Arabs, Ethiopians, etc.) would make sense, however it makes just as little sense to use West Africans to portray Ancient Egyptians (the majority of "African-Americans" are originally from West Africa) as it does to use white Europeans.

text: This comment section makes no sense. Everyone is mad that a bunch of the actors are of European or american nationality, and that it's racist to cast "white" people into what should be "black" roles.  Take a minute and think about exactly what that means. It would be more racist to deny an actor the chance to play a character in this movie because they have lighter skin than it is to have a cast including white people in a historical based fantasy culture set in northern Africa.  What would be racist is an ethnic divide among the cast, something like the villains are all dark skinned and the heroes are all European, something blatantly not apparent here.  People who are mad about European, American, and Australian actors being part of a film that is supposed to take place in a predominantly darker skinned culture are not being racial defenders like they think they are. Not only do they sound whiny and boring, they themselves are actually the ones being racist- except against the people in this movie who do not fit the demographic they decide to impose upon this action/fantasy movie. They are condemning casting directors for choosing white actors for roles that it is assumed should be for darker skinned actors, and actors for accepting to play these parts.   That is a big part of what the modern view of racism is; the denial of opportunities for and judgement of people based on the color of their skin and not the content of their character, or in this case, their prowess as actors.

text: The NBPP once protested American museums where images of King Tut were on tour. They demanded that all images be painted black. Zahi Hawass was the head of Antiquities in Egypt at the time. Black militants even protested a speech he gave in Philadelphia.  After the protest, he told the media that âTutankhamun was not black, and the portrayal of ancient Egyptian civilization as black has no element of truth to it.â He went on to say âEgyptians are not Arabs and are not Africans despite the fact that Egypt is in Africa.â  Over the past five years we have learned a great deal about King Tutâs physical appearance as well as his DNA.  Multiple teams of forensic anthropologists from around the world did facial reconstructions of King Tut, based off his remains. The work was done for National Geographic magazine. Every team concluded that King Tutâs skull could decisively be classified as âNorth African Caucasoid.â  King_TutMore recently, advanced DNA tests proved conclusively that Tutankhamunâs closest living relatives are western Europeans.

text: Ancient Egyptians looked very similar to  lighter middle easterners, today.  Probably, appearing somewhere on the extreme border of what would many  consider 'white' by today's standards.   A type of heavy Mediterranean look, that still exists among more northern middle easterners like a lot of Turks, Persians, Lebanese, Syrians, and Sepharidc Jews (think Andre Bocelli).  Despite common opinion, these types are highly Caucausoid, are just pigmented light brown with swarthiness.   Blondism, was probably never too frequent among ancients, though given the distribution of certain pioneering Caucasoid markers (originating on the Iranian plateau), it was more common than it is today in the middle east.   However, certain groups in the south of the middle east, started mixing with Blacks and hence gained more African features.  Modern Saudi Arabians, Morocoons, and Egyptians, have heavy black admixture.

text: Everyone! The Egyptians are Arabs, which have caucasoid descent (Caucasian) but they were also black Nubians, of African descent. I believe the civilians of Egypt were castes correctly because it was very diverse. The movie is actually so good you get over the racial issue and connect with the characters. Also, when the Greeks came that added to the population of Egypt, even Cleopatra is half Greek half Egyptian with a bit of Macedonian descent. Nobody really knows what color they were because it isn't one shade, because some mummies have red and blond hair (though they did use henna back then to dye the hair). Essentially, my only issue was that everything except the main characters were diverse. Nobody in the cast is Egyptian, as it says on IMDB. I went in the theater thinking the whitewashing was going to make me hate the movie, but it was excellent. This is coming from a person of color who studies Egypt. Thanks!

text: I actually quite enjoyed this movie. I know it has gotten toxic press in the US, and deservedly so, for it's ludicrous casting of a bunch of North Europeans as gods of Egypt and their human subjects, but it is highly entertaining. My kids, 12 and 14, also had a good time. It's a silly matinee-style adventure romp - it doesn't take itself seriously at all: essentially, it's a oddball-couple movie, where a smart-aleck human thief and a pompous, whiny god must team up to save the world. Along the way, the god learns to value human spirit, courage, and humour! The action is over the top and the pacing is non-stop. Leave your brain at home, bring your inner child along, and have fun!

text: I'm not sure how to make this politically correct, but I'm going to give it a shot. It is my understanding, and please correct me if I am wrong, that Egypt was ruled by black Pharaohs until the 14th dynasty when Canaanies took authority, then in the 15th dynasty Hyksos took over, people from West Asia. In the 17th dynasty Egyptians took over again, in the 18th dynasty they expanded their empire. Then in the 21st dynasty Pharaohs of Libyan origin ruled. Until the 25th dynasty when Nubians invaded. They ruled until they were driven back into Nubia. In the 27th dynasty Egypt was conquered by the Persian empire, then eventually they were conquered by the Greeks, then the Romans. As far as I can tell, Egypt has been ruled by many races. At some point in time they were each Egyptian.

text: The MAIN question is, 'why is the cast white?' Everyone that keeps stating that Egyptians were never Black. Please present your proof besides the fact that Egyptians of today are predominantly Arab. If that's your reasoning, then it's unfair and somewhat invalid.  Visually, America's majority race is of Caucasian decent, and like Australia, we can argue that the country is and has always been of whites... But we all know that that isn't historically correct. If you're smart enough to get my point, you'd be able to understand why there is a logical and acceptable speculation that 'Egyptians were once black'. Egypt is located in Africa, not Europe so the use of white actors is unnecessary and just wrong. If you can believe that humans evolved from apes, why are white people so quick to dismiss that Egyptians MAY have been Black at some point? At the end of that day, Egyptians were NEVER white, which brings me back to my main question (and everyone else's), 'why is the cast white?'

Also based on the fact it is a "fictional" movie set in an "alternate universe" where the world is flat , race of actors doesn't seem like it should be a serious issue, I think just the same with Star Wars or any other movie that uses diversity in casting (I'm all for it with race & gender) , even when Fox did their "Grease Live" everyone was supposed to be ok with it (most of us were) but suddenly with this movie it is an issue. I have issue with race as long as their race isn't portrayed as a stereotype or it is derogatory in anyway. I'm more worried about the acting.Lets face it either 300 film, Immortals, Clash of the Titans or Wrath of the Titans not only had just as much CGI but you are hard pressed to find actual Greek or even Mediterranean actors in them. So why is this one a big deal? Again the film is set in an alternate universe where the world is flat, it's not a historically accurate film by any means going in.

The action is for the most part easy to follow and pretty spectacular.   This movie is a big gamble (140 mil budget for an original movie i.e not se/prequel, reboot or adaptation). And I like it, even for originality alone.

text: *More like Gods of Western romanticized fantasies*.    Kemetians had the same skeletal structure as so called subsaharans, spoke an African language,( part of an African language family along with semites), which was related only to those either in,(west African Chadics/Berbers or east African Ethiopians)or hose ancestry came directly out of East Africa (such as the semites). If that's not enough, they painted themselves dark brown, redish brown and later yelloish caramel in complexion. Skin tones that are naturally exist among most African groups in eastern Hemisphere of Africa and elsewhere. Many Great African empires existed AT THE SAME TIME, and after them. So the argument that they were too intelligent to be African is obsolete today as it's always been. Africans are truly all related, yet we are the most genetically diverse people on earth. In other words all features and skin tones can be found among indigenous African groups.

text: " When Seth constantly fails, he plans to humiliate his rival so badly that Horus would be banned from Egypt forever. Seth invites Horus to a party and convinces the teenage Horus to drink more than Horus could normally cope with. When Horus is drunk, Seth seduces him to sleep over the night in one bed together. When lying together in one bed, Seth grabs Horus and rapes him. But Horus has tricked Seth; his drunkenness was staged. He catches Seth's semen with his hands and hides it. Next morning, Horus runs to his Mother, Isis, to tell her what happened. Isis is first speechless with rage and disbelief. Then she decides to return the like on Seth: she cuts off Horus' hand and lubricates Seth's semen on Seth's favorite food (Egyptian lettuce). Totally clueless, Seth eats the manipulated lettuce, then he goes to the divine court to inform on Horus. At first, the divine judges swear at Horus, but when Thot, the scribe of the court, calls for Seth's semen to come out of the body of Horus, the semen instead comes out of the body of Seth. Seth blushes in embarrassment and shock, then flees. Horus is acquitted "

text: Yes, I do agree that the director could have had better visual effects and different colored toned actors and actresses, but I still enjoyed the movie very much. I myself, is obsessed with Egyptian Mythology. Reading the story about the fight between Horus and Set about a million times, I could see why some people didn't care for it as much as they were hoping too. Lets start with the first basic fact, Horus lost only one eye. Not two, one. Even before the fight between Horus and Set, Set cut Osiris into 14 pieces and spread them across Egypt. I know that Horus mentioned it later on in the movie, but the director and writer also did forget another important fact. Isis did not commit suicide, she searched all the pieces of Osiris, brought them together to Anubis, and Anubis made the first mummy. In my opinion, not being a critique either, I thought the effects were decent! Best Egyptian movie I'v seen so far, in my opinion. I was so happy to see this movie and they didn't let me down besides the fact that they out some important facts. I think "Gods of Egypt" should have better reviews and people should look on the positive side! Some one finally found the time to create and Egyptian Mythology movie! I also have been seeing comments of how the actors shouldn't be white and more Egyptian. Well, it would honestly kinda be hard to find actors from the middle east to act in an American made movie. With Isis and other bombing and stuff, it is difficult. This is just my opinion though!

text: I watched this film recently and... yeaaaaaah. It's not awful, like some would have you believe, there are some good qualities, but the majority of the film is pretty much a mess. The pacing in this film is far too fast for me, it's like they're trying to squeeze and obscene amount of lore into the film that either wasn't needed or could have been kept aside. The main human character (can't even remember his name) is not only a poor character (he has like no personality) but isn't acted that well. The actor was pretty stiff throughout and I felt more effort was needed there. The effects looked pretty awful. I know it's fun for the Gods to transform into animal forms but it's essentially pointless and I feel we could have just had good human form fights. I think there needed to be less attention there, the long shots looked gorgeous though. The plot is a bit all over the place, a bit clunky. But I think the film is saved by Gerard Butler and Nikolaj Coster-Waldu. The two of them hand in some really good performances regarding how weak the script is. Nikolaj's character (probably the main one too) lacks some depth or sense of loss I would love him to have but Nikolaj still hands in a really well acted performance and Gerard Butler, whenever he's on screen, is so much of a manly villain it's just fun to watch. Like I said, there's many down sides to this film, including pointless scenes I class as filler, but it's certainly not awful.  (EDIT): I feel like there is a really solid and good idea beneath the poor pacing, effects, characterisation and cramped in lore, I think if people had really cared about this film they would have looked through, cut the pieces that weren't needed, and perhaps handed in a good film. I keep asking whether the Gods really needed to be that tall or transform into those creatures. I get it looks cool or something, but it cripples the film in my opinion. A lot of money could have been spared if it was just human form fighting human form. I dunno, I feel there's certainly a strong film somewhere in there, but it's hidden beneath a lot of crap.

text: Not the best movie when it comes to story and accurate history, but still, an extremely good movie for many unexpected reasons. The special effects were great and really made me experience how great the Egyptian empire was, I can't quite explain it. I could just feel how huge and complex the buildings were and how much effort went into making them. The special effects didn't only look good but they also made a significant emotional impact and that's exactly what movies are about. The whole movie was a lot of fun to watch, I was smiling from the start to the finish. The deaths of some of the main characters were quite unexpected and emotional, very good job there. Even though the whole plot made little sense and was predictable, I could tell the writers and director did that on purpose. They made a fun movie and had fun making it. I can honestly say that this movie, unexpectedly, had a big emotional impact on me. Even though most don't like it, I completely disagree.

text: I don't understand the very bad reviews this movie has gotten. I found it a very enjoyable addition to a genre that's seen way too few valid titles as of late. The sword-and-sandal, adventure from point A to point B movie. It's fun, it's fast, it's pretty to look at, you actually get to care about the characters, and it never takes itself anywhere near too seriously. It's not a deep-thought provoking milestone and definitely doesn't want to be. I actually watched it more than once, which NEVER happens when it comes to the typical CGI-only blockbusting crap this movie has been wrongfully dismissed as.  Oooooh wait, it's probably because of that supremely retarded school of thought that's still pissed about the skin tone of the cast of Exodus. Just look at all the braindead comments below. And all the likes they're getting from the moronic sheeple who think all people who live in Africa (which, just to make sure you know, is kind of a big place that extends far beyond Egypt) should be black, including mythological characters.  That such stupidity and ignorance get generally approved as racial sensibility is almost frightening. It really is a disease of the current times.

text: Long comment coming your way.   Gods of Egypt, for me personally, is an okay movie. It's cliche as heck but I still love it. I watched it over three times, maybe? That's my PERSONAL opinion. You may have not liked it at all.   And the movie has some things that are wrong (such as there are three pyramids in the movie already. But the first pyramid wasn't build until way later). There are many more wrong things but I still enjoyed it. That being said, uneducated people are everywhere in this comment section lol. Why are you trying to sell history when you don't even know what you're talking about?   Seriously stop trying to convert everything into race. Not everything has racism in it. Although maybe, instead of having just one black God, there should have been a fewer darker ones. But still, there should also be fair ones and golden ones.   To the people saying that the Gods of Egypt should be black or Arabian only, you're seriously so uneducated people. First of all, Arab didn't exist until thousands of years after the Egyptian Gods so shut up with the Arabic arguments. Also, the original descendants of Egypt were Coptic. And the Coptic language came after hieroglyphics so that in it speaks for itself.  They consisted of all colors, and facial features. Coptic descendants have a bit of a golden skin tone but they are not black and that's definite. Search it up in the library if you don't believe me.  Not all of Egypt was filled with black people back then. Although today, it contains most African-Americans. The Gods are portrayed mostly correct, except maybe the blonde hair. And like I said, they could have used more darker ones, but the actors were still pretty amazing.
